# Bandit PRD — Deep Technical Review Against 2025-2026 State of the Art

## TL;DR
- **The "repo-native, CLI-authoritative, no-DB" core bet is defensible but only if you swap markdown/JSON files for `git update-ref --stdin` transactions as the actual atomic primitive.** Otherwise the PRD's "atomic CLI operation" claim is fiction the moment two agents invoke the CLI simultaneously, because plain file writes in worktrees have no cross-process compare-and-swap, and committing the registry will produce merge conflicts on the exact lines that encode claims.
- **The lease design is missing fencing tokens**, which Martin Kleppmann's "How to do distributed locking" (blog post, 8 Feb 2016) shows is the only mechanism that makes leases safe under arbitrary process pauses (GC, swap, OS scheduler, LLM rate-limit waits). This is the single most serious correctness gap in the PRD and is independent of how clever the reconciliation logic is.
- **The orchestrator-worker shape is aligned with Anthropic's published architecture, but the PRD has missed three concrete 2025–2026 lessons from that same body of work:** (a) multi-agent systems "use about 15× more tokens than chats" per Anthropic's 13 June 2025 engineering post "How we built our multi-agent research system," so a fixed 15-minute polling heartbeat across multiple agents will burn money on no-ops; (b) observability must be OpenTelemetry `gen_ai.*` spans (Langfuse/Phoenix-style), not MEMORY.md; (c) "fail closed + route to OPERATOR.md" pervasively will manufacture human toil that directly undermines the parallelism throughput goal.

## Key Findings

**A. Concurrency substrate — RISKY as drawn; SOUND if ref-CAS-backed.** Repo-committed markdown/JSON is not a sound substrate for an authoritative lock registry under concurrent writers. Git is not a transactional database across files; two worker sessions committing the registry will produce textual conflicts on the same line ranges, and there is no atomic CAS between "read registry" → "decide claim is free" → "commit claim." The PRD's "atomic CLI operation" is only achievable if it is mechanically backed by a primitive that actually offers CAS. The correct primitive on the Git substrate is `git update-ref` with `--stdin` transactions. Per the official Git docs (git-scm.com/docs/git-update-ref), the three-argument form is true CAS: "Given three arguments, stores the <new-oid> in the <ref>, possibly dereferencing the symbolic refs, after verifying that the current value of the <ref> matches <old-oid>." The `--stdin` transaction form (with `start`/`prepare`/`commit`/`abort` and `verify`/`update`/`create`/`delete` sub-commands) offers explicit transaction atomicity: "If all <ref>s can be locked with matching <old-oids> simultaneously, all modifications are performed. Otherwise, no modifications are performed." Note the documented reader caveat in the same doc — "a concurrent reader may still see a subset of the modifications" — so the multi-ref transaction is atomic for writers but not serializable for readers; you handle this with double-read confirmation. Verdict: **RISKY** as currently written; **SOUND** if files become projections and refs become the write path.

**B. Fencing tokens — ILL-ADVISED as written.** The PRD's lease + renew + stale-cleanup model is exactly the design Kleppmann critiques. He writes (martin.kleppmann.com/2016/02/08/how-to-do-distributed-locking.html): "if the GC pause lasts longer than the lease expiry period, and the client doesn't realise that it has expired, it may go ahead and make some unsafe change." He extends the same argument beyond GC: "if you're feeling smug because your programming language runtime doesn't have long GC pauses, there are many other reasons why your process might get paused. Maybe your process tried to read an address that is not yet loaded into memory, so it gets a page fault and is paused until the page is loaded from disk … Maybe someone accidentally sent SIGSTOP to the process. Whatever. Your processes will get paused." His fix is a monotonically-increasing fencing token, included on every write, where the resource server rejects writes from older tokens: "in this context, a fencing token is simply a number that increases (e.g. incremented by the lock service) every time a client acquires the lock." In Bandit, the "writer" is an LLM agent (long pauses are *inevitable* — rate-limit backoff, context overflow recovery, sandbox suspend, model swap). Without a fencing token on every state-changing op (renew, complete, mark-cleanup-ready, push branch, post comment), a paused agent whose lease expired but never noticed can land external side-effects after recovery. The PRD's "non-destructive cleanup + human recovery" partially mitigates this for the *worktree*, but does nothing for the *registry* or for *external side-effects* the stale agent performs.

**C. Dual canonical sources — RISKY.** Reconciliation-before-every-op between the In-Flight Registry and per-work-item state is a recognized dual-write anti-pattern. Modern practice (event sourcing + CQRS — Martin Fowler, "Event Sourcing," martinfowler.com/eaaDev/EventSourcing.html, 12 Dec 2005; current guidance in Microsoft Learn and AWS Prescriptive Guidance) is to make one stream authoritative and derive the other. The PRD already has an append-only transition history — that *is* an event log, and it should be the single source from which both the registry projection and per-work-item state are deterministically computed. "Fail closed → PM repair" on every disagreement is operationally expensive: every reconciliation mismatch becomes a synchronous block requiring human attention.

**D. Worktree lifecycle — SOUND only with explicit additions; RISKY as currently sketched.** "Worker creates, never deletes; coordinator deletes after verification" is the right shape but git worktree concurrency on a single `.git` has documented race surfaces — `index.lock`, the packed-refs race described by Jeff King on the git mailing list (a `git pack-refs --all --prune` running concurrently with ref reads can produce a view where a loose ref appears missing while the packed-refs file still reflects the old state), and per-worktree HEAD vs shared refs/. The PRD needs:
- explicit `git worktree lock --reason "claim=X"` on creation so `git worktree prune` cannot remove a worktree whose claim is still active;
- a `.worktreeinclude` (Claude Code 2.x convention) for `.env` / secrets bootstrap, or every claim starts in a broken environment;
- a single-writer serializer for `.git/` mutations (per-repo `flock` on `.git/bandit.lock`) because concurrent `worktree add` from N agents is documented to contend on shared refs and `packed-refs`.

**E. Heartbeat scheduler — ILL-ADVISED.** A 15-minute polling heartbeat that wakes an LLM to "claim one stage or no-op" is the worst of both worlds: too coarse to be responsive, too LLM-expensive to be cheap. The Anthropic engineering post "How we built our multi-agent research system" (13 June 2025) states verbatim: "In our data, agents typically use about 4× more tokens than chat interactions, and multi-agent systems use about 15× more tokens than chats." For coding specifically, the Claude Code docs are clearer: "Agent teams use approximately 7× more tokens than standard sessions when teammates run in plan mode, because each teammate maintains its own context window and runs as a separate Claude instance." Even a no-op heartbeat across N agents incurs context bootstrap (5–15K tokens per subagent per Claude Code's published behavior), and AICosts.ai's field report "The Claude Code Subagent Cost Explosion: How One Developer Burned Through 887K Tokens/Min" documents a single 2.5-hour session with 49 concurrent subagents sustaining roughly 887K tokens/minute, illustrating how badly polling-style spawn loops can degrade. The right design is event-driven: trigger on (i) registry change via filesystem watch or post-receive hook, (ii) CI status webhook, (iii) PR review state change, (iv) explicit operator command. Keep a periodic *deterministic, non-LLM* sweeper for stale-claim detection — that's cheap. Only spawn an LLM when there is actually work or a real blocker.

**F. Work Intake Ledger — SOUND as v0 toy; RISKY past modest scale.** The append-only transition-history-with-mutable-current-state pattern *is* event sourcing + CQRS in disguise. Reimplementing it in markdown/JSON files is justifiable for v0 portability but has known scale walls — file-level merge conflicts on the ledger when multiple sessions append simultaneously; growth (real event stores are GB-scale; markdown/CI diffs choke around 1–10MB); and no projection/query layer means every read replays the full history. The deterministic primary_blocker ordering is fine as a *policy*, but the specific eight-tier order is arbitrary and needs empirical justification or it will be litigated forever. Plan the migration to a real append-only log (SQLite WAL, or a Git refs-namespace event store in the style of git-bug, which "stores bugs as Git objects within a repository" and merges concurrent edits via Lamport timestamps + an op-based DAG) *before* you hit the wall, not after.

**G. Fail-closed pervasiveness — RISKY.** Fail-closed is correct for *safety-critical* invariants (don't double-write same surface; don't auto-destroy human work). It is wrong as the *default* for *operational* invariants (registry/work-item disagreement, missing optional fields, ledger drift), where graceful degradation + automatic mechanical repair is the SRE-canonical answer. The PRD already concedes "mechanical repair" exists but bounds it to "already-approved artifacts" — too narrow. Escalation rate to OPERATOR.md will dominate engineer attention and erode the parallelism win.

**H. The "no database, repo-native, CLI-authoritative" bet — SOUND for v0 small-scale; RISKY past 5–10 concurrent agents.** Steelman: git history is a free audit log; humans can grep the registry; no hidden authority; offline-capable; works across forks. Attack: Ádám Sándor at Container Solutions (blog.container-solutions.com/gitops-limitations, "GitOps: The Bad and the Ugly," 2 Sep 2020) names the failure mode directly: "In an enterprise environment, the number of GitOps repositories and/or configuration files will grow enormously. As a result, combing through text files is not a viable option for answering important questions." And on the write-side: "Git, however, is designed for manual editing and conflict resolution. Multiple CI processes can end up writing to the same GitOps repo, causing conflicts." Bandit's "multiple LLM agents writing the same registry" is structurally the same problem. The PRD's "DB may index later but not be authority" escape hatch is only viable if the DB is a pure projection of an event log that is itself canonical and append-only — which the ledger almost is, but the registry currently isn't.

## Details

### Layer-3 first-principles observations

**The PRD has confused "atomicity" with "fail-closed-on-conflict."** True atomicity is mediated by a CAS primitive: an operation either fully completes or has no effect, with a single linearization point. Fail-closed-on-conflict means after *detecting* an inconsistency, refuse to act. These are not equivalent. The PRD repeatedly asserts "one atomic CLI operation" but the actual described mechanism is "read state, check expected matches, write new state, append history entry" *across multiple files*, with *no underlying CAS*. Between the check and the write, another CLI invocation can interleave. The fail-closed check catches the *next* operation, but the racing pair can both have written. This is a more basic layer error than the fencing-token issue.

**The dedicated PM coordinator is a single point of orchestration tax.** The orchestrator-worker pattern is well-attested — Anthropic's research system "uses a multi-agent architecture with an orchestrator-worker pattern, where a lead agent coordinates the process while delegating to specialized subagents that operate in parallel," and "outperformed single-agent Claude Opus 4 by 90.2% on our internal research eval." But that same post is explicit: "Multi-agent systems work mainly because they help spend enough tokens to solve the problem … token usage by itself explains 80% of the variance." Translation for Bandit: every claim/release/escalation routed through the PM costs tokens. At small scale, fine. At >5 workers + a recurring 15-min cadence, the coordinator's context window will rot (the well-documented context-rot phenomenon of long agentic sessions), and the strict role separation will cause handoff fidelity loss between sessions unless briefs are formally checked for sufficiency.

**"No GUI, no DB" is conflating two different concerns.** "No GUI" is a UX choice (CLI-first). "No DB" is an authority choice. These can be decoupled: SQLite-backed authority + markdown projection for humans is a coherent design. The PRD bundles them, forcing the wrong thing (markdown as authority).

**TDD/RED-evidence-first cannot prove concurrency correctness.** Test-driven development gives you regression coverage on cases you thought of. Concurrency bugs are by definition the cases you didn't think of. The literature is unambiguous — Jepsen, FoundationDB's simulator, TigerBeetle's VOPR (running 1,000 CPU cores 24×7 and simulating "2 millennia of simulated time" per the Amplify Partners DST primer), WarpStream's use of Antithesis. If Bandit's invariant is "two concurrent claims on the same surface cannot both succeed," that should be checked by a model checker (FizzBee, TLA+) or property-based testing with a fault-injecting scheduler, not by two example tests.

### Comparison to current orchestration tools (April–May 2026)

By spring 2026 the multi-agent coding orchestrator field is crowded: Conductor (Melty Labs), Microsoft Conductor (YAML deterministic orchestration with explicit "Orchestration should be deterministic and inspectable. Not an LLM making routing decisions"), Composio AO (spec-driven verification with autonomous PR handling), Claude Squad, Crystal (deprecated Feb 2026 → Nimbalyst), Vibe Kanban (community-maintained after Bloop shut down April 2026), Cursor 2.0 (up to 8 concurrent agents native via worktrees or remote VMs), Google Antigravity (agent-first IDE with Mission Control), Anthropic's Multiagent Sessions API (beta header `managed-agents-2026-04-01`, coordinator delegates to context-isolated agent threads), and Claude Code's experimental Agent Teams (shared task list + status flags + file locks + worktrees).

Bandit's positioning:
- **Most differentiated:** the explicit "PM agent that cannot implement," "operator inbox as markdown," and "fail-closed on dual-source disagreement" combination. No mainstream tool ships this exact shape.
- **Convergent:** worktrees-per-agent is universal. Claim/lock primitives are universal. Anthropic's Agent Teams ships "file locking to prevent conflicts," the closest mainstream analog to Bandit's work-surface reservations.
- **Where Bandit is behind:** OpenTelemetry is now the de-facto AI agent telemetry standard (Langfuse, Phoenix, OpenLLMetry, OpenLIT all converge on `gen_ai.*` semantic conventions and OTLP); deterministic-orchestration YAML (Microsoft Conductor); spec-driven verification (Composio AO); token budget enforcement at the orchestration layer (Claude Code's `/usage`).

### Specific PRD claims that don't survive scrutiny

- "Atomic CLI operation" across multi-file writes without an underlying CAS primitive: not actually atomic; just fail-closed-on-next-conflict, which is different.
- "Non-destructive stale cleanup" as the safety guarantee for expired leases: incomplete without fencing tokens, because external side-effects (PR push, branch update, posted comment) cannot be un-done from the worktree.
- "Reconciliation before every op" as performance-acceptable: at scale, two canonical reads per CLI invocation × N agents × 15-minute cadence = constant filesystem churn for almost-always-no-op outcomes.
- "Repo-native is portable across projects": true for the schema, false for the merge-conflict surface area; every repo with parallel agents will collide on the same ledger line ranges. Container Solutions' GitOps critique applies directly.
- "Markdown/JSON files are CLI-authoritative": semantically fine, mechanically incomplete — "authoritative" under concurrency requires a CAS primitive that files don't provide.

## Recommendations

**Phase 0 — correctness blockers, must do before v0 ship:**

1. **Replace the file-write claim primitive with `git update-ref --stdin` transactions** on a `refs/bandit/*` namespace. Each claim is a ref; renew/release/transfer is a CAS via `update SP <ref> SP <new-oid> SP <old-oid>` or `verify` in a stdin transaction. Markdown files become projections regenerated on every successful transaction. This single change fixes the "atomicity asserted but not achievable" problem with no new infrastructure.
2. **Add fencing tokens.** Monotonic per-claim (trivially: the claim ref's update count or the ledger entry index). Required on every state-changing op (`--expected-token`). Every external side-effect (PR push, branch update, comment) tags itself with the token. Stale-leaseholder writes are mechanically rejected.
3. **Add idempotency keys** (client-generated UUIDs) on every create/renew/release/complete. Combined with fencing tokens, this gives effectively-once semantics.
4. **Add wait-for-graph cycle detection** on work-surface reservations. Two work items each reserving a surface the other needs is a deadlock the PRD's overlap detector won't catch.

**Phase 1 — during v0:**

5. **Refactor to single-source-of-truth event log.** The transition-history ledger is canonical; the In-Flight Registry and per-work-item state are deterministic projections. Eliminates the entire "two canonical sources reconciled" failure class.
6. **Replace 15-minute polling with event-driven triggers** (filesystem watch on `.bandit/`, git hooks, CI webhooks, explicit operator command). Keep a cheap *non-LLM* sweeper for lease expiry.
7. **Emit OTel `gen_ai.*` spans** as a first-class output of every CLI op. Trace per agent session; span per claim/renew/release; child spans per LLM call. Ingestible by Langfuse/Phoenix/Honeycomb out of the box.
8. **Token budgets at the claim level.** Each claim declares a token ceiling; CLI refuses to spawn an LLM that would exceed repo-level budget.

**Phase 2 — before scaling past 5 concurrent workers:**

9. **Capability-enforced registry write isolation.** Either (a) registry lives outside the worker's worktree (worker sees a read-only projection), (b) sandbox-enforced filesystem allow-list (NVIDIA/Edera microVM style), or (c) signed transition entries with key-based rejection at projection time. Honor-system rules ("agents must not edit the registry directly") will fail.
10. **Deterministic simulation testing harness** for the claim/release/reconcile state machine under fault injection (clock skew, filesystem latency, rate-limit pauses). Property invariant: at most one active claim per surface per fencing-token-monotonic window.
11. **Plan the SQLite-WAL or refs-namespace event-store migration.** Define the trigger threshold explicitly (e.g., ledger >5MB or >500 entries or >50 concurrent items) and pre-write the migration. Do not let it become a panic-mode change.

**Benchmarks that would change these recommendations:**
- If Bandit will only ever serve 1–2 agents on one repo: Phase 2 is overkill, Phase 1 items 5–8 are nice-to-have, Phase 0 is still required.
- If you can prove via DST that markdown-only writes never race in your deployment topology (always single-machine, single-OS-user, single-process serializer), Phase 0 item 1 can be deferred — but the burden of proof is on the design, and proof must be a model-checked invariant, not a TDD test.
- If the PM coordinator empirically consumes <10% of total token spend in production, the "coordinator is a bottleneck" concern dissolves. Instrument first.
- If OPERATOR.md escalations exceed ~5/day per operator, the "fail closed pervasively" stance is generating intolerable toil and the mechanical-repair scope should widen.

## Caveats

- The orchestrator-tools landscape is evolving monthly; specific products named (Conductor, Crystal/Nimbalyst, Cursor 2.0, Antigravity, Anthropic Multiagent Sessions, Microsoft Conductor) are accurate as of April–May 2026 but feature parity will shift.
- The "git refs as a CAS lock service" recommendation is correct per official Git documentation (git-scm.com/docs/git-update-ref guarantees the three-arg form and the `--stdin` transaction semantics), but no major coordination system explicitly markets itself this way. git-bug, Gerrit's NoteDb, and git-appraise use refs for *data* storage with merge-based (CRDT / op-based) concurrency, not as a fencing-tokened lock service. Bandit would be doing something modestly novel; the upside is that ref-CAS is genuinely atomic per documented semantics.
- Anthropic's published numbers ("15× tokens," "90.2% improvement," "80% of variance from token usage") are from a research workload, not coding. Claude Code's own docs put agent-teams overhead at ~7×. The order-of-magnitude conclusion (multi-agent ≠ free) stands regardless.
- The fail-closed critique assumes throughput is a priority. If Bandit's design priority is *correctness over throughput by design* (regulated environments where every disagreement *should* halt for human review), "fail closed everywhere + OPERATOR.md" is correct and my "RISKY" verdict in section G is wrong. The PRD does not make this priority explicit and should.
- I have only reviewed the PRD summary, not the implementation. Some critiques may already be addressed in code not surfaced in the PRD text.
- The Container Solutions / Atlas GitOps critiques cited are about Kubernetes-state GitOps, not coordination state directly; the analogy is structural (mutable, high-frequency, multi-writer state on a Git substrate) and the failure modes (merge conflicts, query difficulty, drift) transfer cleanly.